 Wealden hall house

A Wealden hall house is a type of medieval house commonly found in the Weald of Kent, Sussex and Surrey. Dating from the 14th century, they are rectangular, often timber-framed buildings with a large hall and a smaller private room, or solar, on the first floor. Often the roof only covered the hall, with the solar being an open gallery. They were the home of wealthy farmers and merchants, and their size reflects this.

Wealden hall houses are characterised by:

their rectangular plan, often with a projecting porch;
a great hall and a solar;
the great hall has an open hearth and windows to the front and rear walls;
a staircase leading up to the solar;
the roof is often thatched;
they are often built of timber framing with wattle and daub or loam fillings, though some are brick;
a partition, sometimes half-height, separating the hall from the service rooms;
a projecting upper floor, jetty, sometimes supported on brackets, and a gable end chimney stack.

As the Wealden area is rich in clay, many Wealden hall houses have brick walls, sometimes with a stone slate roof. In the 16th century, many Wealden hall houses were heightened, and their windows changed to conform to the new fashionable style of casement windows. Jetties were often added, and roofs were extended to cover the newly created first floor rooms. Chimney stacks were added, and in many cases the open hearths in the hall were removed.

A Wealden hall house in Burwash, Sussex
Wealden hall houses are found in many parishes in the Weald. Almost every parish in the Rother and Hastings area has at least one example, and there are several in the neighbouring districts. They are often concealed behind later extensions and therefore not easily visible. Despite this, many survive remarkably unchanged, with the exception of the windows.

In regions further away from the Wealden area, such as the High Weald of Kent, or the area around Horsham, West Sussex, Wealden hall houses are less common, and are usually located on high ground, such as around Goudhurst, Kent, or Hartfield, East Sussex. In these areas they are usually built of timber framing with brick infill, and have tile roofs. They have narrower proportions than those in the sandstone areas, and often have gabled ends.

