The McPherson Playhouse (also known as The Chrysler Theatre, formerly Capitol Theatre and later The Royal Theatre) was a theatre building in downtown Victoria. Owned by the City of Victoria it has been leased to the Canadian College of Performing Arts since February 2013 while major renovations were being planned for the facility. Previous tenants include Greater Victoria's municipal opera company Pacific Opera; a number of local amateur community groups such as Belfry Theatre and Intrepid Theatre; and professional troupes including the Vancouver Island Symphony Orchestra.^{[5]}

## HistoryEdit

Built in 1948 under contracting supervision of WJ Beaton & Son Builders with architectural work undertaken by William Randolph Smith^{[6]}, the theatre originally seated between 1570-1650, mainly on the main floor and balcony levels. This did not include either loge seating at either side of stage left or right nor seats for patrons with disabilities who were located under the stairs leading up to the three galleries (balconys). There are two additional staircases that rise above the back wall of both these galleries and exit just behind where each upper row of seat begins, enabling speedy egress if required. An open area beneath the proscenium arch provides access into frontal entrances along each gallery level.^{[citation needed]} On opening night the film A Dangerous Profession starring Ray Bolger, Lucille Ball and Jack Lemmon was showing, which included an intermission break when everyone adjourned to adjacent streets to view the illuminated facades. In July, 1948 plans called for a one million dollar expansion that would see new offices built over the theater lobby entrance to form part of what became Eaton's Centre Victoria at Johnson Street. However it appears this plan never came to fruition. At time of writing a digital display screen mounted high on its outer wall faces onto Broad and Blanshard Streets shows announcements about upcoming productions and performances within Victoria City Hall . Although used primarily for musical concerts in more recent years there have also been many rock acts performing at capacity crowds over the years. During 2004-2005 major restoration work took place to return the interior
